== Familiarizing with spaciousness through provisional meditation techniques

After you've recognized the nature of mind, it may be just fine to use effort, to use your conditioned mind, to get used to spaciousness, to get used to this nice fresh awareness. And so we have all types of probably hundreds of techniques that you can use to get used to your real sort of nature---what they call the natural state. Okay? 

#heading(level: 3, outlined: false, [Dzogchen Object Meditation])

And so let's start off with just picking an object. I'll pick my mollusk, since I didn't have it in my hand already. Just wrap it up here and put it in front of me. Alright, so we'll do one minute of object meditation, okay? Hopefully everybody's ready. Just relax.

And remember, this is Dzogchen object meditation, so instead of focusing on the object, notice how the object is in your awareness already. For one minute, we'll just stay with our object.
#btw[The sangha practices the instruction for a few moments].

Okay, very nice. And so the degree of your distraction there is measurable, right? You can see how easy that was, or how difficult that was to stay with the object, or allow that object to stay with you. When I say Dzogchen Samatha, I mean Dzogchen object-based Samatha. Of course, Dzogchen Samatha is stabilizing in clear light awareness itself.

#heading(level: 3, outlined: false, [Body Scan in Śūnyatā])

And so now we'll do what's typically called Vipassana as a body scan in Sūtrayāna, okay? So body scan is just starting from the crown of your head and just slowly working your way through, going down inside the brain, the forehead, the eyes, the nose, the lips --- bringing them in awareness. Then the neck and shoulders, allowing that tension to release, the arms, down to the forearms and the hands, the chest and stomach, back

We're just getting in touch, right, with these aspects of our experience. Saying: "come into the house of awareness." You may leave it at the stomach for a second, bringing the very intricate nervous system down there, lots of organs coming into awareness. Then down to the pelvis area, the sitting muscles, the private area, thighs, down to the legs and the feet. Whole body now in awareness.

Then if you zoom out a little bit, your whole energy, the subtle energy body. So that's a little Sūtrayāna, Śamatha, Vipassana, the stability and insight practices.

#heading(level: 3, outlined: false, [Isolating a Thought])

Now let's isolate a thought. Now that allegedly we have our stability and we have a wider scope of visibility, let's pick a thought, "Rainbows are colorful." That will be our very simple thought, and only have this one thought, as if we're kind of a robot that can only have one line of code. So we have this one thought: "Rainbows are colorful."

Now notice the canvas, the aquarium, the space in which this thought happens. "Rainbows are colorful." Notice if you're adding anything to any more thoughts to this, or having resistance. Maybe a picture of a rainbow is popping up, that's fine. We really just want to get in touch with the basis that's holding this thought, that's capable of presenting this thought.

"Rainbows are colorful." Notice how it kind of echoes out within the mind. Mhm. So the thought itself is the thought movement, the energy of the mind, and the part of your mind that's serving as the basis, _gzhi_. This is the Buddha nature, because it's still there as you're having the thought. So it's this beautiful cognitive basis.

#heading(level: 3, outlined: false, [Isolating an Emotion])

So let's try it with an emotion. Uh-hu. Let's make ourselves a little joyful. That may be difficult, but then deal with whatever emotion is here for you already. So where's the emotion happening? The same place, same canvas. Yeah so thats... we can kind of isolate an emotion. We've isolated a thought.

#heading(level: 3, outlined: false, [External Senses and Weight])

And now let's focus on something externally. I'll pick a drum. Yeah? I'm picking a drum sitting right in front of me. Now just relax, release your object. Notice how your mind is still pulling towards that object, typically. That sense weight, okay? We can do that with sounds, we can do that with sights.

If you see something very attractive, even repulsive, you can notice your mind's engagement. There's an engagement there, that's what we're interested in. And the pure basis awareness is still here, holding that engagement.

So whether it's a taste, a smell, a tactile sensation, something we see or hear, we can measure, so to speak, this weight that we have invested. It's not good or bad, we just want to see our weight.

And now I have a choice. I have a little bit of freedom. I can invest into that drum or not. So those are the five sense aspects of consciousness, combined with the sixth, thinking and emotional, that Manovijñāna, as it's known in Sanskrit. 

And the seventh, we'll move on to the seventh aspect of consciousness now, which is the self.

#heading(level: 3, outlined: false, [Invoking the Sense of Self])

So we'll sit here again in our clear, open canvas, and we're going to deliberately invoke a sense of self. You can say, "I'm meditating. I'm meditating." And that little feeling of "me" meditating, that's the thought. That's what we're isolating within awareness.

And then when you leave these things in awareness, pure presence starts to open up, doesn't it? That little sense of self goes away, and now you're really open and non-dual. So you start to become undivided. So you can isolate that sense of self, that conditioned pattern of reemerging apprehension.

And those are all effort-based practices dealing with the eight consciousness model, the Abhidharma. But here, now you can just relax into awareness and allow all of these things at once to just be there within your basis, within this canvas.

And if you're having some kind of thoughts that are occupying your mind, just look at them with an awareness, let them disappear, and rest in the pure presence that opens up.

If you feel very disturbed, who's disturbed? I'm the one that's disturbed. Bring that into awareness, let it disappear, rest in presence. If you're feeling love or hate. Who loves? Who hates? Where's the love? Where's the hate? Bring it into awareness, let it be in spaciousness and pure presence like that.

So these are all just cognitive contractions that are softening up. We're not deleting the emotion, we're not deleting the self, we're not deleting thoughts or anything like that. We're just lessening the contraction.

And this way, we're coming into our whole mind, and we have freedom there. Most importantly, somebody cannot kidnap your mind. Somebody cannot submit you into a kind of hypnosis without your consent. This goes so deep into sovereignty within dreams, okay? The more you get used to your whole mind, you will reclaim that sovereignty. That means nobody can get in your head anymore, not even desire, anger, any of these things.

So those are... that is the eight aspects of consciousness within awareness, kind of our mechanics. And these are a little bit effort-based techniques to get used to the nature of your mind. You don't have to use them.

You could go outside and get upset about something, that could be your familiarization with awareness. So your sadness, your empathy, your nostalgia, all these things can be embraced within the canvas that I'm referencing, right? But we're just offering nourishment. We're offering spaciousness and ineffability to our experience, so that our experience isn't confined by some kind of conceptual boundary constraints. Mhm.

So I think that's about it. Those are phase two, if you want to get more specific, phase two little tricks that you can use to familiarize with the view after introduction. Okay?

So introduction means you had a little, oh yeah, or aha, some kind of acknowledgement that you saw something you hadn't noticed before. That acknowledgement is undeniable. We can all prove, "Oh yes, I've seen the nature of my mind. I was pointed to it, or I recognized it, yes for sure." You can validate that.

But then you have to familiarize with it so that your patterns can go out. Otherwise you're going to be submissive to your patterns. You're always going to be under programming, involuntary programming. So now that you've seen your whole mind, you've got to allow time for that conditioned fire to burn out. 

That's the one phase that people tend to ignore in the contemplative worlds, that we can just jump right into enlightenment. And I wish we could just, oh, everything's enlightening, everything's perfect. But then this cycle, this momentum, this inertia of sadness comes back, or this inertia of incompletion returns. Well, what are you going to do with that? How are you handling that? In Dzogchen we let that be nourished within just letting it be. Just letting it be here in awareness, let it reveal itself, let it heal itself.

Yeah, so they use this in cognitive science, this technique of letting be. They use this in mindfulness. But the difference is here, you have the largest scope possible, the very nature of experience and reality as awareness. So now you can really let the whole thing be into a kind of cosmic Nirvāṇa, which includes this fourth foundation of mindfulness, the environment, our reality. I think we can tread into those waters, many of you can. Let the mind and the environment liberate, self-liberate, okay?

So that's my little spiel, that's my little talk today, just reminding, preserving a little bit about some of these techniques.

And yeah, of course we have this manual. It gets attributed to me, but many people worked on that. And then you can use those four phases as a guideline to contextualize your practice if you need to, and things like that.

